quizzes.textContent:
[h1]display: inline[/h1]

An [b]inline [/b]element only takes up as much width as necessary, and does not force line breaks.
[b]The CSS:[/b][code format="css" codeId="563"]p {
   display:[b] inline[/b];
}[/code]
The code above will produce the following result: [img id="2648" width="100%"]
[note]Setting the display property of an element only changes how the element is displayed, not what kind of element it is. So, an inline element with [b]display:block[/b] is not allowed to have other block elements inside it.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Make the element with the id="mystyle" disappear:
[!raw!]
#mystyle {
   display: {0};
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]display:none  [/h1]

[b]display:none[/b] hides an element, so it does not take up any space. The element will be hidden, and the page will be displayed as if the element is not there.

[b]The HTML:[/b][code format="html" ]<h1>This text will not display, as we set the value to none.</h1>
<p>Headline of this paragraph is not displayed, as we set the value to none.</p>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b][code format="css" codeId="564"]h1 {
   display: [b]none[/b];
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2649" width="100%"]
[note]There are plenty of other display values, such as [b]list-item[/b], [b]table[/b], [b]table-cell[/b], [b]table-column[/b], [b]grid[/b], etc. Just play with values to see the difference. [/note]
